                        <!-- The items in AM 736 I 4to contemporary with the
hemispherical world map comprise
1) a description of the three continents, sometimes called the Icelandic Geographical Treatise (f. 1r); 
2) an Old Norse text – now for the most part illegible – on the three Biblical Magi (f. 1r);
3) an Old Norse note on the error in the Julian calendar (f. 1v);
4) the Old Norse tidal note (f. 1v); 
5) a rota diagram that shows the orbits of the seven planets (f. 1v)
6) and a circular map of Jerusalem (f. 2r). 

The later addition,
dated c. 1350, is a description of the Church of the Holy Sepulchre
and the environs of Jerusalem (f. 2v). It is productive to examine these
items, serially, for what they can tell us about the map’s intellectual
environment and its inclusion in this anthology. -->
                    </head>
